			<a name="17"><font face="verdana" size="3" color="#9f3215"><b>    Gordon on crossteaming PvP</b></font>
			<br>
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			<b><a href="mailto:catalyst@everlore.com">Catalyst</a>
			</font><font face="verdana" size="2" color="#9f3215">
			</b></font>[<font face="verdana" size="1" color="black">8/13/2000 12:11:06 PM PST</font>] <font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			<b><a href="newsinfo.asp?ID=197624">
			8 Comments
			</a></b></font>
			<br>
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black"><Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/004396.html">PvP Teams Revisited: Thoughts on Crossteaming</a></B><P>

<I>Hello,<P>

I posted this in another thread but it seems to warrant its own.<P>

The biggest difficulty in regards to PvP in EverQuest is that EverQuest is, and will remain, a primarily PvE (Player versus Environment) game. The addition of PvP to the game should not change the basic fundemental mechanics of EverQuest. PvP in EverQuest has to result in "EverQuest with PvP" rather than "PvP EverQuest", if you get my point. <P>

One of the largest issues on the PvP Teams servers is the subject of cross-teaming. Players of different teams get together for battles. Due to the PvE focus of the game, this has to be allowed for sake of game balance. Though some have suggested that cross-teaming, either in groups or guilds, not be allowed, it's something that will need to remain for the PvE game.<P>

The problem comes in when cross-teaming is applied to PvP. Cross-teaming creates a situation that is often referred to as the "invulnarable healer" scenario. Basically, one group of PCs (Team A) attack a group of people on Team B, while supported by a healer from Team B. In this fashion, you have a situation where a member of one team is taking an active role in the deaths of members of their own team.<P>

There is another "invulnarable healer" scenario that is more common and often just as bad as the cross-teaming scenario. This one revolves around a group of players from Team A attacking a group from Team B, while supported by a healer/buffer who is far superior in level to anyone from Team A or Team B. For example, a group of level ~20 trolls go on a killing spree in Greater Faydark, while supported by a level 50 healer/buffer. The problem in this case is that someone out-of-range is directly contributing to the deaths of players below their range.<P>

On Friday, I spoke with one of the programmers about possible solutions for the PvP Teams servers, assuming that people in general believe these issues to be a problem. Suffice it to say that there is no easy solution. Each one has its disadvantages and "loopholes". For an example of some of the solutions:<P>

1. Disallow cross-team buffing/healing<BR>
2. Disallow out-of-level (+/- 8) buffing/healing<BR>
3. Combination of 1 & 2.<BR>
4. Redefine "Teams" servers to GvE (good versus evil) servers and implement idea #1 on that basis, rather than on cross-teaming.<P>

The problem with all of these solutions is that they have an undeniable impact upon the PvE aspect of the game. <P>

The final and best idea that we were able to come up with allows things to continue as they are now in regards to PvE, and only places restrictions on the basis of PvP. In this idea, any player who has taken damage from another player would not be able to be healed/buffed/receive any beneficial spells from anyone who wasn't on their own team or in the +/- 8 level range for a given amount of time (a few minutes), or until they zoned. <P>

In the cross-teaming "invulnarable healer" scenario, the person from Team B would be able to support people from Team A for PvE engagements, however once a member of Team A took damage from another team, they would not be able to receive support from anyone on Team B for a few minutes. In a real game scenario, the maurading band of trolls in Greater Faydark couldn't be healed/buffed by a high-elf assuming that they were taking damage in their attacks. <P>

In the out-of-level scenario, that same band of level ~20 trolls wouldn't be able to receive support from a 50th level cleric. <P>

There are some disadvantages to this, such as in the following:<P>

4 Trolls are grouped with a high-elf fighting PvE encoutners in a dungeon. Humans come in and "slap" the trolls every so often thus keeping the high-elf from assisting them. Perhaps this should just be a disadvantage for cross-teaming in general. Perhaps this is just a risk that people take from grouping with the enemy.<P>

What are your thoughts on these ideas? What other issues do you see causing problems in regard to this idea? Do the benefits (e.g. reaffirming the servers as PvP Teams) outweigh the potential disadvantages? <P>

-Gordon</I><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<I>If we could keep on target here and discuss the proposed solution, that would be great. I'd rather not see this thread turn into a discussion about faction penalties, as that's a subject for another thread.<P>

-Gordon</I>
</blockquote>
